{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a168928a-c71a-4488-af87-9526f936fe42","content":"## CPU Baseline Instruction Sets in .NET\n\nThe .NET runtime has been **raising its minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level**. Starting with .NET 9, Linux x86-64 requires **x86-64-v2** (SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT). A further bump to **x86-64-v3** (adding AVX, AVX2, BMI2, FMA, etc.) would exclude pre-Haswell CPUs.\n\n**Your 2012 hardware** is likely Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge era — these support v2 but **not v3**. That's your failing node.\n\nYou can verify on the host:\n\n```bash\n# Check supported microarch levels\n/lib/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 --help 2>&1 | grep \"x86-64-v\"\n\n# Or check for specific instructions\nlscpu | grep -i -E \"avx2|avx |fma|bmi\"\n```\n\n### Your other platforms\n\n| Target | Status |\n|---|---|\n| **x86-64 Linux (2012 hardware)** | ❌ Missing required ISA extensions |\n| **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)** | ✅ Arm64 baseline hasn't changed |\n| **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm64)** | ✅ Armv8-A is still the Arm64 baseline |\n\n### Options\n\n1. **Retire the old hardware** — simplest long-term fix.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** for those specific nodes while upgrading elsewhere.\n3. **Build a custom .NET runtime** from source with a lower baseline (unsupported, not recommended for production).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cadf6a0d-f149-42c1-a4d9-70a6977c9c4c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets. This is a known issue with .NET's evolving hardware requirements. Let me explain what's happening.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the baseline CPU requirements for x86-64 Linux. Specifically, .NET 9+ requires x86-64-v2 as the minimum instruction set baseline on Linux, which includes SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. This was further discussed for .NET 10+.\n\nLet me think about the timeline:\n- .NET 7: x86-64-v1 baseline (original x86-64)\n\n\n- .NET 8: x86-64-v1 baseline\n- .NET 9: raised to x86-64-v2 on Linux\n- .NET 10 and 11: continue with x86-64-v2\n\nThe error \"The current CPU is missing one or more of the baseline instruction sets\" is exactly what the .NET runtime throws when your CPU doesn't meet these requirements. The issue is that hardware from 2012 might lack SSE4.2 support, which is required for x86-64-v2.\n\nI'm considering whether .NET 11 might jump to x86-64-v3 instead, which would require AVX and AVX2 instructions that didn't arrive until Intel Haswell in 2013 and AMD Excavator in 2015. Since .NET 11 hasn't released yet, I'm not certain what the actual baseline will be. The most documented change is .NET 9 raising the Linux x86-64 baseline to x86-64-v2, so if they were already on .NET 10, they should have hit this already—unless .NET 11 pushed it further to x86-64-v3, which would require AVX2 that 2012-era CPUs lack. Rather than speculate about .NET 11 specifics, I should give them a clear explanation: .NET has been progressively raising its minimum instruction set requirements, and this error means their CPU doesn't support what the runtime now demands. I'll keep this focused and practical for the user.","outputTokens":1569,"requestId":"A475:BB4CA:237EA7E:2732384:6A03D878"},"id":"a0f578ca-f576-4149-b1ab-41596e7ec4eb","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:49:15.044Z","parentId":"af46d357-0f5f-419a-8268-501fd203c4fc"}
